â†’ Fast, connectionless, unreliable protocol
ğŸš— Analogy: Like sending postcards â€” each one travels separately, and if one is lost, you just move on.
3. âš¡ QUIC (Quick UDP Internet Connections)
â†’ Modern protocol built on top of UDP
Why QUIC was created:
1. TCP is reliable but slow due to:
2. Connection setup (3-way handshake)
3. Head-of-line blocking (waiting for missing packets)
4. TLS encryption happening separately
QUIC solves this by:
ğŸŒ€ Combining TLS encryption + transport in one layer (faster handshake)
âš¡ Built on UDP, so itâ€™s connectionless but still reliable & ordered
ğŸš€ Provides multiplexing (multiple streams in one connection)
ğŸ”„ Allows connection migration â€” your session stays alive even if your IP changes (e.g., switching from WiFi to mobile data)
âš¡ Example: When you load a website using HTTP/3, itâ€™s actually using QUIC under the hood â€” faster, secure, and resilient.
ğŸš— Analogy: Like an express delivery service thatâ€™s as fast as UDP but as reliable as TCP â€” with built-in security and no traffic jams.

